<TITLE> Three suspended WASA engineers get 15 years for graft </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Chittagong, Dec 02 (bdnews24.com)  A Chittagong court cleared chief engineer of Chittagong WASA Shafikul Islam of corruption charges and sentenced four others to 15 years each in the same case Sunday. Judge SM Solaiman of the Divisional Special Judge's Court for Chittagong found Shafikul Islam innocent after hearing the case. Thirteen witnesses testified in the case. The court also ordered the confiscation of property owned by the four and fined them Tk 4.25 lakh each. The convicted WASA officials, who were suspended earlier, are supervising engineer Mohammad Shafiullah, assistant engineer AKM Abdul Quddus, deputy divisional engineer Abu Taher. The fourth is a contractor named Faruk Ahmed. Abu Taher and Faruk Ahmed have yet to be arrested. State counsel Zahirul Islam told bdnews24.com that the court had convicted the four of the charges of misappropriating Tk 17 lakh in public funds. Mobinul Islam, an official of the former Bureau of Anticorruption, filed the case on June 17, 2004, alleging that the money had been misappropriated in 2000 from a WASA project setting a pipeline from the city's Panchlaish Girl's School to Toktar Pul area. ACC investigating officer Jahangir Alam submitted the chargesheet of the case on Sep 27 and the trial began with chargeframing on Oct 31, 2007. bdnews24.c
